It's Day 1! Welcome everyone. Have I told you how awesome it is for you to say yes and commit to a 30 Day Yoga Journey? Seriously - you are awesome. Today's theme is motive. 

We often rely on motivation to come from an outside source. But what if you realized that it could come from within?

We begin with focusing on motive because aligning with the reason why you are here sets the tone for what you will experience on the journey. 

If you are here to smell like a fart and feel lousy then you will likely accomplish that. 

A student‚Äôs motive to go to school is to learn. 

What is your motive for join TRUE? Now, wait! Stick with me!If you do not know your MOTIVE yet - that is 100% OK! It‚Äôs perfect. It will likely reveal itself and feel amazing when it does. If it does. We are here to uncover and circle back to that feeling of‚Ä¶ you. 

The true you. 

The real you. 

~ Share with us your motive down below! What is your reason for committing to TRUE? 


PS: 100% okay to not know your motive yet!!!

This is my third 30-day yoga journey. I did 30 days of yoga last fall and it took me something like 75 days because I needed to repeat many of the practices. Then I did Home in January of 2020 and I loved that. I mostly, but not completely did that in 30 (plus a few) days. The great thing is that I've done some yoga every day since then. And what a difference it's made in my body, but also in my spirit and my mind. I am so grateful. This set of 30 practices I started just after Home finished, but then life had other ideas about how I should be and many changes have come down the pike--for me and for the world. Now on this new start, I am learning how to support my very strong Mom who is far away and very recently widowed, learning how to be a fatherless child (at age 54--my dad, who was a free spirit in so many ways while living is now all spirit--and I feel his legacy moving through me and my family daily), and finding the need to reinvent my livelihood in the face of COVID-19 along with what seems like the rest of the planet. I am daily finding many silver linings in all of these "clouds." and Yoga everyday with an invitation to contemplate the inner world is so helpful. Thank you so much, Adriene and everyone who supports this lovely gift we give each other.
I am starting this journey to become truly present with myself...I work so hard at being present with others, yet I am scarcely present with myself.

Wow, I can't believe I sweated so much for such a slow-paced practice! It was so nice to move through Warriors slowly. New experience.

I'm gonna say how, maybe ir's useful for someone:
I imagined the metaphor from Headspace ad, which is watching the traffic go by. I imagined each thought as a car, and the driver was the part of my personality that the thought was about. The key was to imagine the DRIVERS to have my thoughts. For example, a student driver was worrying about exams. Thinking about the drivers made it much easier!

Day 1/30. I've only taken 3 yoga classes in my life and the last one was over 10 years ago. I knew going in that this was going to be a challenge. The poses themselves were very doable, yet for me also physically challenging. I could feel how tight, and so out of alignment every part of my body is. This was upsetting (although I already knew I was out of alignment and out of shape), but it was also encouraging that I could feel down to the cellular level and pinpoint specific places and really FEEL my body and soul.  When you had us pull our arms in to hug ourselves the first time, tears immediately came to my eyes and a couple of them traveled down my cheeks.  I think this is going to be a very challenging yet cleansing experience for me, probably more so in the area of emotional/mental growth.  At the end when we brought our hands up to our third eye I saw a diamond shaped bright light that had a slightly blue or indigo tint to it. Thank you for so generously offering this challenge and all of your videos to us.

I am 59 yr 3 mo old, 65 in tall and a 136 lb woman in a 238 lb body. I have literally been in bed for 26 mo after ending a 7 yr experiment in returning to the entry level career I left in 1986. I have gained about 50 lbs in this depression episode & am up from 147 on June 28, 2012 when I had minimally invasive open heart surgery to repair my prolapsed mitral valve. I took my first yoga class in 1978 when my body weighed 136 lb and was 18 years old. I never became an expert but have gone to many fitness classes, been quite fit and weighed from 112 to 248 lb. in that time. Last Tuesday I went to a yoga class 5 mi up the river from where I live in rural Virginia. It may not have been quite as significant as college graduation but just getting there may have been the most significant thing I have ever done! I went to two studio classes this week but I can't afford to go that much so I am going there once a week and practicing at home between. I started the original 30 Days on Friday. Yesterday at about 22 minutes in Day 2,  I realized I might have to find a way to do 45 days of yoga. I literally cannot move from down dog to runners lunge due to the weakness of my body & it's bulk. So much of my postmenopausal weight is around my waist that it is like trying to work out with an tire tube around my middle. I just found this new offering so I will go through some beginning sessions that I have found and try to do 15 or 20 minute sessions a couple of times during the day to get my strength built up & then start this new 30 Days series. I cannot even say how thankful I am for your YouTube classes. Yoga classes are not affordable for low income people like me where I live so you are literally saving my life. I CAN NOT believe I am actually part of this yoga journey after discovering Adriene last month and doing the Yoga Revolution in my own time.

I have so much of a wonderful expectation as to what this yoga journey will entail and on the first day, I have not been disappointed.  

I came to the mat late (s I only completed this session less than an hour ago) so I feel as though I am already a day behind, but I am in a good place.

When it comes to my motive behind doing this challenge, I am happy to say, I am doing this as a way of keeping myself from sitting on the couch and to continue with my wellness journey that I began last month.

In one of my entries on the revolution journey, I said this my Eat, Pray, Love journey and for me, Yoga is Pray ... I discovered through the revolution journey that I needed to be more kind to myself and this is what I am continuing to practice through this journey.  

I am staying true to myself by treating myself with kindness but at the same time challenging myself through the 30 days.  At times, I know I will be pushing myself to be switched on for the day, but I have made the commitment that I will work through these sessions and take each day as they come.  I am not creating a false image of what I want to achieve at the end of this journey, I am going to be taking each day as it comes and allowing these moments on the mat to be my time to connect with my breathe and with realities that may or may not come up on this journey.  Reality on the last journey was to be kind to yourself ... 

If there is any life lessons to be learnt on this journey, I am open to accept them just like I did while on the revolution journey.  It is amazing but sometimes, you just need someone to say something that you had been telling yourself or something that you had been needing to hear because you know that over time it is a truth you had been searching for but you didn't know what it was ...  

Coming to the end of the revolutionary journey, I realised I was treating myself as though I had overcome my cancer treatment and I am fine and life was back to where I was before ... but in reality, I needed to find more time to recover and I found out that my mental health had been affected to the point of being diagnosed with depression ... so finding yoga through my Doctor has made me slow down, accept where I am now and that I need to take time out for me.  I am still finding it hard to slow down, but with these minutes on the mat, I feel as though I am connecting to what is important for me now ...

I live with a lot of pain and a lot of fatigue for no good reason. My motive is to see how my body responds to daily stretching,  breath and mindfulness of the body to see what changes. Today my shoulder was hurting like it had a serious injury, and my neck and back were locked up so much that it was like being in a painful, metal brace that was wrapped around my torso. Stretching into the pain is interesting. It hurts like hell, but it's a good hurt, and afterwards I feel better for a while.

I wonder if I could change my body so that I don't have to suffer like this if I kept a daily practice. I've felt momentary relief before, and my motive is to see what happens after a month. Namaste

oh adriene, i've been away from you for too long. about a month and a half. i re-started doing pilates in an attempt to shape my body more quickly for my upcoming teeny courthouse wedding + bali honeymoon which is awesome, but i've been missing you. and doing this video just made me realize how much. i've been trying not to focus negatively on my body too much, but i gained ~13% of my "usual" body weight over the past few years. all good happy relationship weight, but it's lingered longer than any weight spike i've ever had in my life before, and i've felt somewhat out of place in my body. and can feel myself becoming more and more critical of my body the longer the weight stays on me. when you asked what our motive was at first i didn't know. and then while you were talking it flitted into my mind, so right and so real and so TRUE-- my motive is to spark (or feed or lean into, if you will) my light. take it out from under it's proverbial bushel. i realized while i sat listening to you that that's what i really want when i picture myself on my honeymoon and the day i marry my husband and the day after that and the day after that. i want to feel playful and alive and connected and strong and beautiful in my body. i want to smile and laugh and be graceful and WOMAN. i want to be LIT. so, my motive is to lean into and feed my light. <3

I had a dream last night that I was a new firefighter recruit. There was a pretty big group of about 30 of us. As the alarm rang and a group of us hopped onto the fire truck for our first real call, I felt a flash of worry, that I don't know what I'm doing and what if I mess up. But then I was quickly assured that we were all in the same boat, and we will make some mistakes as we learn, and that's okay. What followed was such a deep sense of purpose and drive, of tight-knit camaraderie, that I was making a real difference and what I did mattered. That I was fulfilling my purpose.


I hadn't felt those things in over 7 years. At all. I've been trapped under a thick and paralyzing depression that has refused to let up despite throwing every conceivable type of therapy at it. It's been sapping every bit of my life energy, leaving me not much more than a hollow shell many days. In this dream it was like something woke up within me, and it ironically couldn't happen unless I was asleep. In reality I have zero desire to be a firefighter, but I long to regain that sense of purpose. And so that's my motive, starting day 1 of this yoga program and heading into the new year. To tap into that sense of purpose. To wake up.

Hello Adrienne, and my YWA community members! My motive in doing this is to find peace, love, and self-care in my everyday life. I would like to learn to take things slow and to take a more active role in my life and in myself -- to take the time to check in with my body and my mind and the world. I also am searching for a deeper love and sense of connectedness with my body. I have been overweight my whole life, and have often struggled with a sort of lack of agency over my body -- feeling like I couldn't love and respect it and possess it wholeheartedly as my own because it was "ugly" or "unhealthy." I want to improve my health, but I feel that first I need to improve my relationship with myself. Yoga has helped me to accept my body as my body, and helped me to own it.

I want to say a huge thank you to Adriene and everyone in this community for supporting me, even if they didn't know they were doing it. Finding ways to "work out" or even just to find some movement can be hard when you're overweight, because you feel so ashamed and as if you don't belong. So thank you to Adriene for making movement about self-love, for making me feel as though my body is lovely, and as though I can do anything. Thank you to Adriene for teaching me to find what feels good rather than to punish myself for my perceived faults. This has truly been a breakthrough for me. I'm so excited to take things even further during "True."

I am so excited to start this journey! The past couple of months have been pretty hard mentally for me, I have realised a lot of things that were hard to accept but very necessary for growth in 2018. I easily get overwhelmed by big goals and tend to procrastinate until it's too hard for me to make any progress at all, but I am determined to make this year all about baby steps and a thirty day yoga journey to start it is going to be perfect!
The goal isn't to have done fifteen hours of yoga throughout January, it is to show up for myself every day. Then before I know it, I can look back on January, and see that I have, in fact, completed roughly fifteen hours of yoga, and I can be proud of what I have accomplished instead of dreading the journey to get there. Instead of looking at daily yoga as yet another thing to cross off on my to do list, I am going to embrace it as something to look forward to in order to be able to be the best me I can this year.
